, and Microsoft=E2=80=99s malware discovery in Guam.

On to the update:

Micron=E2=80=99s China Ban
------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-bans-mi=
cron-as-supplier-to-big-chinese-firms-citing-national-security-5f326b90 ) :

China is banning major Chinese firms from buying from Micron Technology, sa=
ying its products pose a major national-security risk. The move caps an inv=
estigation that underscores strained relations between Beijing and Washingt=
on. The Cyberspace Administration of China said Sunday its review of Micron=
 products found =E2=80=9Csignificant security risks=E2=80=9D that would aff=
ect national security and warned operators of key Chinese information infra=
structure=E2=80=94such as telecommunications firms and state-owned banks=E2=
=80=94against purchasing the company=E2=80=99s goods.

Micron makes memory chips =E2=80=94 both DRAM (used for processing) and NAN=
D (used for storage) =E2=80=94 and is generally strongest in consumer produ=
cts like PCs and smartphones; that right there should shield the company fr=
om incurring a major hit in terms of revenue, at least in the short term. A=
t the same time, from what I have heard, Chinese server OEMs are already pa=
using orders not just for Micron memory directly, but also for components t=
hat include Micron memory; it will likely take some time to figure out what=
 exactly is banned and what isn=E2=80=99t, and to what extent those bans sp=
ill-over into seemingly unrelated products.

Meanwhile, from Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05=
-27/us-won-t-tolerate-china-s-micron-chips-ban-raimondo-says ) :

Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo said the US =E2=80=9Cwon=E2=80=99t tolerat=
e=E2=80=9D the recent decision by Chinese authorities to ban chips by Micro=
n Technology Inc. in some critical sectors, using her sharpest language yet=
 to describe Washington=E2=80=99s reaction. =E2=80=9CWe see it as, plain an=
d simple, economic coercion,=E2=80=9D she said, using a phrase both sides h=
ave lobbed at each other amid recent tensions. =E2=80=9CWe won=E2=80=99t to=
lerate it, nor do we think it will be successful.=E2=80=9D

The latest technology tensions between the two global powers kicked off las=
t Sunday, when the Cyberspace Administration of China warned operators of k=
ey infrastructure against buying Idaho-based Micron=E2=80=99s chips, saying=
 it found =E2=80=9Crelatively serious=E2=80=9D risks after concluding a rev=
iew it announced in March. That followed a sweeping ban by the US in Octobe=
r on exports to China of high-end chips and the technology to make them.

The brief statement from China=E2=80=99s Cyberspace Administration ( http:/=
/www.cac.gov.cn/2023-05/21/c_1686348043518073.htm ) didn=E2=80=99t specify =
why specifically the Micron chips were banned; the safest assumption, parti=
cularly given the brevity of the security review, is that this is retaliati=
on for last fall=E2=80=99s chip ban. The fact that Micron is an obvious tar=
get is an even better reason to make this assumption: memory is commoditize=
d, which means that Micron products will be relatively easy to replace with=
 =E2=80=94 ideally from China=E2=80=99s perspective =E2=80=94 homegrown alt=
ernatives or, more likely, South Korean chips.

To that end, two dueling stories on that topic, starting with the Financial=
 Times ( https://www.ft.com/content/93ba7f32-35df-4b5f-a14f-263b26b1f854 ) =
:

Seoul has signalled it will not intervene to stop South Korean companies Sa=
msung and SK Hynix from filling in a market gap after China imposed a ban o=
n US chipmaker Micron, in an escalation of the tech battle between the supe=
rpowers. Last month, the White House quietly asked South Korea to urge its =
chipmakers to hold back from boosting sales to China if the sale of Micron =
products was restricted by Beijing. But policymakers in Seoul on Monday sai=
d they were unwilling to wade into the dispute and would defer to the compa=
nies.

Then Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05-27/south-k=
orea-to-avoid-cashing-in-on-china-s-us-chipmaker-ban ) , a few days later:

South Korea will avoid capitalizing on China=E2=80=99s ban on a US chipmake=
r, seeing the move by Beijing as an attempt to drive a wedge between Seoul =
and Washington, according to a person familiar with the situation. The Sout=
h Korean government won=E2=80=99t encourage its memory-chip firms to grab m=
arket share in China lost by Micron Technology Inc., which has been barred =
for use in critical industries by Beijing on national security grounds, sai=
d the person, who asked not to be identified as the topic is politically se=
nsitive.

The second story is framed as a step-back from the first, but frankly, they=
 seem like the same stance to me, and a reasonable one. The South Korean go=
vernment isn=E2=80=99t going to get involved, beyond saying what the U.S. w=
ants to hear, in large part because it=E2=80=99s not at all clear what the =
government could do otherwise. Take the example of the component maker I he=
ard about above: if that component maker starts buying South Korean memory =
so that it can continue selling to Chinese server OEMs, then have Samsung o=
r SK Hynix done anything wrong or, more importantly, done anything even det=
ectable?

This goes back to why it makes sense for China to target Micron: memory is =
largely a commodity, which means they can punish a U.S. company without hur=
ting their interests, but that also limits the damage to Micron as well; th=
e more that South Korean memory suppliers sell to Chinese firms, the less s=
upply they will have to sell elsewhere, even as Micron has more supply than=
 they might have otherwise to fill in the resultant gap.

To that end, Raimondo=E2=80=99s comments seem like a mistake to me on a few=
 counts. First, the hypocrisy is pretty embarrassing: I suppose there is a =
difference between banning sales to a particular country versus banning imp=
orts into your own country, but it=E2=80=99s pretty rich for the U.S. to co=
mplain about any China-related chip actions at this point. Second, it seems=
 unwise to bluster about how the U.S. =E2=80=9Cwon=E2=80=99t tolerate=E2=80=
=9D this action; yes, the U.S. has power over both South Korean memory make=
rs given that both rely on U.S. licenses to operate fabs located in China, =
but given that the market will probably solve this particular issue for Mic=
ron why threaten action that isn=E2=80=99t necessary?

The fact of the matter is that the U.S. continues to hold nearly all of the=
 cards when it comes to Chips and China ( https://stratechery.com/2022/chip=
s-and-china/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnB=
