Neeva Gives Up on Search
------------------------

From the the company blog for Neeva ( https://neeva.com/blog/may-announceme=
nt ) , the for-pay search engine founded by former SVP of Google Ads Sridha=
r Ramaswamy and former VP of YouTube Monetization Vivek Raghunathan:

We started Neeva with the mission to take search back to its users. Having =
worked on search and search ads for over a decade, we sincerely believed th=
at there was space for a model of search that put user and not advertiser i=
nterests first=E2=80=94a private, ads-free experience.

Building search engines is hard. It is even harder to do with a tiny team o=
f 50 people who are up against entrenched organizations with endless resour=
ces. We overcame these obstacles and built a search stack from the ground u=
p, running a crawl that fetched petabytes of information from the web and u=
sed that to power an independent search stack=E2=80=A6

But throughout this journey, we=E2=80=99ve discovered that it is one thing =
to build a search engine, and an entirely different thing to convince regul=
ar users of the need to switch to a better choice. From the unnecessary fri=
ction required to change default search settings, to the challenges in help=
ing people understand the difference between a search engine and a browser,=
 acquiring users has been really hard. Contrary to popular belief, convinci=
ng users to pay for a better experience was actually a less difficult probl=
em compared to getting them to try a new search engine in the first place.

Three days later Snowflake announced it was acquiring Neeva ( https://www.c=
nbc.com/2023/05/24/snowflake-snow-earnings-q1-2024.html ) for an undisclose=
d amount =E2=80=94 i.e. not much =E2=80=94 which leads to a couple of takea=
ways:

* First, here is yet another example that new products have to be massively=
 better than an incumbent to even gain trial from customers; being just a l=
ittle bit better isn=E2=80=99t nearly enough, particularly when your primar=
y vector of differentiation is something consumers don=E2=80=99t care about=
.
* Second, to that point, here is yet another example that consumers do not =
value privacy as a differentiating factor worth switching for, particularly=
 if that factor comes at a monetary cost.
* Third, that Neeva was almost certainly sold for less than it raised to an=
yone-other-than-Apple is yet another example that the iPhone maker has no i=
nterest in competing with Google in search, and would much prefer to be pai=
d billions of dollars a year to give customers what they would probably pre=
fer to use regardless.

Neeva actually seems like a pretty good acquisition for Snowflake, particul=
arly given Neeva=E2=80=99s recent push into LLM-driven conversational inter=
faces. SVP of Product Christian Kleinerman said on Snowflake=E2=80=99s earn=
ings call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4607174-snowflake-inc-snow-q1-=
2024-earnings-call-transcript ) :

The broad vision that we communicated to all of you over the last several y=
ears is Snowflake is on a mission to extend its capabilities, so we can bri=
ng computation to happen close to the data. It has evolved us into an appli=
cation platform. And a core use case for applications is not only search an=
d search enabled experiences, but with the advent of generative AI is the n=
otion of conversational experiences. The folks from Neeva are the ones that=
 are going to power or help us accelerate the efforts around Snowflake as a=
 platform for search and conversational experiences, but most importantly w=
ithin the security perimeter of Snowflake with the customers=E2=80=99 data =
so that they can leverage all this new innovation and technology, but with =
the safety on the privacy and security of the data.

Remember, Microsoft just announced Fabric ( https://stratechery.com/2023/wi=
ndows-and-the-ai-platform-shift/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI=
6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhd=
GVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hl=
cnkuY29tLzIwMjMvd2luZG93cy1hbmQtdGhlLWFpLXBsYXRmb3JtLXNoaWZ0LyJdfSwiZXhwIjo=
xNjg4MTM1MDE1LCJpYXQiOjE2ODU1NDMwMTUsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkucG=
Fzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc=
