zRSCxIgh5ciMNw4cFyjAQ ) :

The reality would =E2=80=94 may =E2=80=94 be more complicated. I think Goog=
le would likely be better off licensing its technology in the long run; ind=
eed, it seems blindingly obvious that Google and Uber should have been part=
ners. In fact, there is a strong analogy to Apple and Google: it ought to h=
ave been Apple making iPhones and Google providing services, to the benefit=
 of both. In that case Google wanted more, and the price it paid was dear: =
default access to the most attractive part of the market. One can certainly=
 make the case that Google made the same mistake here: by wanting it all it=
 lost the easiest path to a very lucrative market; a prize of punitive dama=
ges would be a very paltry one in comparison.

It took a bunch of lawsuits and a completely new set of executives, but the=
 blindingly obvious partnership is now a reality! Let=E2=80=99s see if it t=
akes a longer or shorter amount of time for said partnership to actually am=
ount to anything.

